   "source": [
    "# Motion tracking\n",
    "\n",
    "For a more detailed description see: <https://www.phenopype.org/gallery/projects/motion-tracking/>"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "phenopype successfully imported the following plugin dependencies:\n",
      "torch\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "import phenopype as pp\n",
    "import os \n",
    "import pandas as pd\n",
    "import trackpy as tp ## install with `pip install trackpy`\n",
    "\n",
    "## my root directory - modify as you see fit \n",
    "os.chdir(r\"D:\\science\\packages\\phenopype\\phenopype-gallery_exec\")\n",
    "\n",
    "## my laptop has a small screen, so I use a smaller phenopype window\n",
    "pp._config.window_max_dim = 800"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Initialize motion-tracker\n",
    "\n",
    "Video analsyis in phenopype works a bit differently than images. Rather than making a project, videos are analyzed one by one. However. to batch process images, you can recycle some of the code. Here, I show how to analyze a single video though. First we initialize the motion tracker with our example video, and specify the video output."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "\n",
      "\n",
      "--------------------------------------------------------------\n",
      "Input video properties - \"isopods_fish.mp4\":\n",
      "\n",
      "Frames per second: 29.97000099996667\n",
      "N frames: 450\n",
      "Length: 00:15 (mm:ss)\n",
      "Dimensions: (960, 540)\n",
      "Colour video: True\n",
      "FourCC code: avc1\n",
      "--------------------------------------------------------------\n"
     ]
    },
    {
     "name": "stdin",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Save folder phenopype\\motion-tracking does not exist - create?. y\n"
     ]
    },
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "\n",
      "\n",
      "--------------------------------------------------------------\n",
      "Output video settings - \"isopods_fish.mp4\":\n",
      "\n",
      "Save name: isopods_fish_v1.mp4\n",
      "Save dir: D:\\science\\packages\\phenopype\\phenopype-gallery_exec\\phenopype\\motion-tracking\n",
      "Frames per second: 29.97000099996667\n",
      "Dimensions: (960, 540)\n",
      "Colour video: True\n",
      "Format (FourCC code): avc1\n",
      "--------------------------------------------------------------\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "mt = pp.motion_tracker(r\"data_raw\\motion-tracking\\isopods_fish.mp4\")\n",
    "\n",
    "mt.video_output(save_suffix=\"v1\", dirpath=r\"phenopype\\motion-tracking\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Then we create a mask to only include the gravel area - this will exclude the walls where reflections and floating particles may result in false positives. A second mask in the center of the area can later be used to compare whether isopods tend to stay more on the side (shy behavior) or whether they move freely (bold behavior). In each captured frame there will be an entry for each isopods in which area it was detected. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "masks = pp.preprocessing.create_mask(mt.image, label=\"full\", annotation_id=\"a\")\n",
    "masks = pp.preprocessing.create_mask(mt.image, label=\"center\", annotations=masks, annotation_id=\"b\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Now we set up two `tracking_methods`: the \"fish\" method is set to `\"single\"` and will only capture the largest object, whereas the isopod method will capture all objects smaller than 30 pixels. You can play around with `blur` and `threshold` settings to see if you can get better results. The `operations` argument is used to return specific information of the detected objects. We specify a few parameters to retrieve phenotypic information of the isopods. Later, we can then analyze which phenotypes were foraged on which sediment background.  "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "fish = pp.tracking_method(label=\"fish\", remove_shadows=True, min_length=30,\n",
    "                          overlay_colour=\"red\", mode=\"single\", \n",
    "                          blur=15, # bigger blurring kernel\n",
    "                          threshold=200 #higher sensitivity\n",
    "                         ) \n",
    "isopod = pp.tracking_method(label=\"isopod\", remove_shadows=True, max_length=30,\n",
    "                            overlay_colour=\"green\", mode=\"multiple\",\n",
    "                            blur=9, # smaller blurring kernel\n",
    "                            threshold=180, # lower sensitivity\n",
    "                            operations=[\"diameter\",  # isopod size\n",
    "                                        \"area\",      # isopod area\n",
    "                                        \"grayscale\", # isopod pigmentation \n",
    "                                        \"grayscale_background\"] # background darkness\n",
    "                           )"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Finally, we pass the methods on the detection settings, and also activate *consecutive masking* (`c_mask=True`). This option will prohibit repeated detection of objects when several tracking methods are applied. For example, inside the detected fish-area sometimes isopod objects are detected, due to artifacts or incomplete subtraction results. Consecutive masking will \"block\" an area after the first method has been applied - the order by which methods are applied matters. The following settings will create a rectangle shaped mask around the fish with a 200 pixel border."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "-----------------------------\n",
      "Detection method \"fish\":\n",
      "\n",
      "{'blur_kernel': 15,\n",
      " 'label': 'fish',\n",
      " 'max_area': inf,\n",
      " 'max_length': inf,\n",
      " 'min_area': 0,\n",
      " 'min_length': 30,\n",
      " 'mode': 'single',\n",
      " 'overlay_colour': (0, 0,\n",
      "                    255),\n",
      " 'remove_shadows': True,\n",
      " 'threshold_value': 200}\n",
      "-----------------------------\n",
      "\n",
      "\n",
      "-----------------------------\n",
      "Detection method \"isopod\":\n",
      "\n",
      "{'blur_kernel': 9,\n",
      " 'label': 'isopod',\n",
      " 'max_area': inf,\n",
      " 'max_length': 30,\n",
      " 'min_area': 0,\n",
      " 'min_length': 0,\n",
      " 'mode': 'multiple',\n",
      " 'overlay_colour': (0, 128,\n",
      "                    0),\n",
      " 'remove_shadows': True,\n",
      " 'threshold_value': 180}\n",
      "-----------------------------\n",
      "\n",
      "\n",
      "\n",
      "\n",
      "--------------------------------------------------------------\n",
      "Motion detection settings - \"isopods_fish.mp4\":\n",
      "\n",
      "Background-subtractor: MOG\n",
      "History: 60 seconds\n",
      "Sensitivity: 10\n",
      "Read every nth frame: 5\n",
      "Detect shadows: True\n",
      "Start after n seconds: 0\n",
      "Finish after n seconds:  - \n",
      "--------------------------------------------------------------\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "mt.detection_settings(methods=[fish, isopod],\n",
    "                     c_mask=True,\n",
    "                     c_mask_shape=\"rect\",\n",
    "                     c_mask_size=200,\n",
    "                     masks=masks)"
   ]
  },

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Analyzing tracking results with _trackpy_\n",
    "\n",
    "Now we can use the frame-wise coordinates to construct trajectories of isopods and fish. For this we will use the excellent _trackpy_ library (<https://soft-matter.github.io/trackpy>). Trackpy is a Python package for particle tracking in 2D, 3D, and higher dimensions. \n",
    "\n",
    "Here you need to find out what works best for your specific case - the larger search_range or memory are, the more challenging it is for the algorithm to find a solution, especially if you have many moving objects in your video. With only one, it should be ok to go to high values. The filtering step is optional, but can be useful to eliminate spurious trajectories."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 8,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "## matplotlib requires rgb format, but opencv/phenopype use bgr. we need to convert our static background image\n",
    "import cv2\n",
    "\n",
    "mt.image = cv2.cvtColor(mt.image, cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB) "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 9,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Frame 89: 1 trajectories present.\n"
     ]
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 432x288 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "## fish trajectories\n",
    "fish_df = coordinates[coordinates['label'] == \"fish\" ] # just use the fish-coordinates\n",
    "traj_fish = tp.link_df(fish_df, \n",
    "                       search_range = 100, #how for to look for the fish in the next frame. can be large if fish swims fast\n",
    "                       memory=60, # how long can the fish sit still\n",
    "                       neighbor_strategy=\"KDTree\", \n",
    "                       link_strategy=\"nonrecursive\")\n",
    "traj_fish_filter = tp.filtering.filter_stubs(traj_fish, \n",
    "                                             threshold=20) # filter out particles that were only found 20 times\n",
    "\n",
    "## plot \n",
    "plot = tp.plot_traj(traj_fish_filter, \n",
    "                    superimpose=mt.image)\n",
    "fig1 = plot.get_figure()\n",
    "fig1.savefig(os.path.join(working_dir, mt.name + \"_fish_trajectories.png\"), dpi=300)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "For isopods, we perform one additional step: because we know that we have 20 isopds, we remove frames with more particles."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 10,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Frame 89: 8 trajectories present.\n"
     ]
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 432x288 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "## isopod trajectories\n",
    "df_isopod = coordinates[coordinates['label'] == \"isopod\" ] # just use the isopod-coordinates\n",
    "df_isopod_filtered = df_isopod.groupby(\"frame\").filter(lambda x: len(x) < 20)  # filter out frames with too many points\n",
    "traj_isopod = tp.link(df_isopod_filtered, \n",
    "                      search_range = 50, # isopods are slow, so this can be small. especially important when using \"multiple\"\n",
    "                      memory=200, # isopods can sit still longer\n",
    "                      neighbor_strategy=\"KDTree\", \n",
    "                      link_strategy=\"nonrecursive\")\n",
    "traj_isopod_filter = tp.filtering.filter_stubs(traj_isopod, \n",
    "                                               threshold=10) # each particle needs to be found at least 10 times \n",
    "\n",
    "##p lot\n",
    "plot = tp.plot_traj(traj_isopod_filter, superimpose=mt.image, colorby=\"particle\")\n",
    "fig1 = plot.get_figure()\n",
    "fig1.savefig(os.path.join(working_dir, mt.name + \"_isopod_trajectories.png\"), dpi=300)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",

   "source": [
